<Layout title="About — Santa Monica Prop R">
  <h1>About this site</h1>

  <h2>What is Proposition R?</h2>
  <p>
    Proposition R is a City of Santa Monica ballot measure that voters approved on
    November 6, 1990. It requires that <strong>30% of newly constructed multifamily
    housing</strong> in the city be affordable to low- and moderate-income households,
    and that <strong>at least half of that affordable share</strong> go to low-income
    households (so 15% of all new multifamily units). The
    <strong>Affordable Housing Production Program (AHPP)</strong>, codified at Santa
    Monica Municipal Code <strong>&sect;9.64.150</strong>, implements the measure and
    requires an annual report on its progress to the City Council.
  </p>
  <p>
    The mandate is measured against all new multifamily residences completed citywide
    each fiscal year &mdash; not only units that received city funding, and even
    including 100% market-rate projects that complied by paying an in-lieu fee.
    Single-family homes and accessory dwelling units (ADUs) are excluded.
  </p>

  <h2>What this site shows</h2>
  <p>
    Two views of the data drawn from those annual reports:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>
      A <strong>time series</strong> of the cumulative Proposition R achievements:
      total residences, market-rate versus affordable counts, the affordable share,
      the very-low- and low-income share, city-funded affordable units, and whether
      Prop R compliance was achieved each fiscal year (FY 1994-95 through FY 2024-25).
    </li>
    <li>
      An <strong>interactive map</strong> of multifamily developments by address,
      grouped into three categories &mdash; <strong>completed</strong>,
      <strong>under construction</strong>, and <strong>planning approvals</strong>
      &mdash; each styled distinctly.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Data source</h2>
  <p>
    All figures are transcribed from the City of Santa Monica's annual Proposition R
    reports, "Information Item" memos to the Mayor and City Council from the Director
    of Housing and Human Services. These are public records. The cumulative
    achievements table (Attachment B) is restated in full each year; the most recent
    report is the authoritative copy of the complete series.
  </p>
</Layout>
